Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents automatically in a LATEX document using the `hyperref` package:
```css
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
\usepackage{hyperref}

\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction.

\section{Section 1}
This is Section 1.

\subsection{Subsection 1.1}
This is Subsection 1.1.

\subsection{Subsection 1.2}
This is Subsection 1.2.

\section{Section 2}
This is Section 2.

\end{document}
```
In this example, the `hyperref` package is used to create clickable links in the table of contents. The `\tableofcontents` command generates the table of contents automatically based on the sections and subsections in the document. When the document is compiled, a clickable table of contents will be generated at the beginning of the document.

To draw a chessboard in LaTeX, we can use the `chessboard` package. Here's an example code that sets up the required packages and draws a chessboard:
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{chessboard}
\usepackage{xcolor}

\begin{document}

\begin{center}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\chessboard[
    setfen=startpos,
    fields/.append style={
        draw=black,
        fill=white,
        font=\small,
        inner sep=2pt,
    },
    pieces/.append style={
        font=\small,
        inner sep=2pt,
        fill=white,
        circle,
        outer sep=2pt,
    },
]
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{center
```

