public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
    if (n == 0) {
        return false;
    }
    if (n == 1) {
        return true;
    }
    if (n % 3 == 0) {
        return true;
    }
    return isPowerOfThree(n / 3);
}
```
The idea behind the solution is to use binary search to find the exponent x such that 3^x = n. If n is a power of three, then we can find such an x. Otherwise, we can show that no such x exists.

We start with the base cases:

* If n is 0, then it is not a power of three.
* If n is 1, then it is a power of three.
* If n is not 0 or 1, then we can divide n by 3 and recursively check if the result is a power of three. If it is, then the original number n is also a power of three. If not, then n is not a power of three.

Using binary search, we can eliminate the middle cases and reduce the number of recursive calls. This results in a more efficient solution compared to using loops or recursion.

